Task 6 – Resource Cleanup
The problem in Task 6 is to ensure that the container runtime and kernel memory monitor can shut down completely and safely, without leaving any residual resources or inconsistent state. After all containers have been started, monitored, and stopped in previous tasks, the system must:
- Reap all child processes in the supervisor so that no zombie (`Z`) processes remain.  
- Terminate logging threads cleanly, after flushing any remaining log data from the bounded buffer to disk.  
- Release all user-space resources, including pipes, control sockets, log file descriptors, and dynamically allocated heap structures used for container metadata and logging.  
-Clean up kernel-space state in the memory monitor module by removing all entries from its monitored-process list and freeing associated memory before `rmmod`.  
Formally, Task 6 asks you to verify and demonstrate that, after a full demo run and shutdown sequence, there are no zombie processes, no lingering threads, no open control sockets or stale FDs, and no leftover kernel monitoring entries.

					
